> > I'm not sure there's a lot we can do here...
> 
> I think we can dedupe messages. That's a general pattern that all of our logging everywhere should handle well.

We already log errors in the rpc layer as DEBUG, so do we even need to log errors in this module as ERROR? Errors here are likely to be like this one, where it didn't work because the document was changed while it was still processing it or things like that. Turning up to DEBUG and you see the exact same message that would have surfaced here:

```
[DEBUG][2026-06-15 06:36:04] /usr/local/share/nvim/runtime/lua/vim/lsp/rpc.lua:445      "rpc.receive"   { error = { code = -32801, message = "Content modified." }, id = 31, jsonrpc = "2.0" }
[DEBUG][2026-06-15 06:36:04] /usr/local/share/nvim/runtime/lua/vim/lsp/rpc.lua:445      "rpc.receive"   { error = { code = -32801, message = "Content modified." }, id = 32, jsonrpc = "2.0" }
[ERROR][2026-06-15 06:36:04] ...local/share/nvim/runtime/lua/vim/lsp/semantic_tokens.lua:407    "semantic_tokens"       { code = -32801, message = "Content modified." }
```

> Agree that it shouldn't be required. However this be a worthwhile optimization. Previously, `vim.diagnostic` significantly improved performance by explicitly sending a `$/cancel` request, preventing the Lua language server from pointlessly diagnosing code in outdated buffers.

For requests, the notification is `$/cancelRequest` which can be sent with a `client:cancel_request(id)` call, which is already done for semantic tokens whenever a new request is sent before the previous result was received. It doesn't help because LuaLS triggers the cancellation from the didChange notification itself, so even if we _immediately_ fire `$/cancelRequest` after the didChange, there's still a race, and I don't think it actually helps anything because LuaLS is still canceling the pending request internally anyway. The result is an error for the pending request:

